'''Elijah Henry Just''' (born 1 May 2000) is a New Zealand professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[winger (association football)|winger]] for [[Scottish Premiership]] club [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]] and the [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand national team]].<ref name="soccerway">{{Soccerway|474216}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Western Suburbs===
Just joined the Olé Academy, then run by [[Declan Edge]] moving from Palmerston North to live at the academy. He played for [[Western Suburbs FC (New Zealand)|Western Suburbs]] in the [[Central Premier League|Central League]] that features teams from the lower half of the [[North Island]] of New Zealand.<ref name="background">{{cite news |last1=Hyslop |first1=Liam |title=Moulding a Kiwi Messi: Ole Football Academy's neverending football quest |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/domestic/106870068/moulding-a-kiwi-messi-ole-football-academys-neverending-football-quest |accessdate=18 November 2019 |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=21 September 2018}}</ref> Just was part of the team to win the [[Central Premier League#Past Champions|Central League]] in 2017,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hyslop |first1=Liam |title=Western Suburbs win Central League title with two games to go |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/sport/95260902/western-suburbs-win-central-league-title-with-two-games-to-go |accessdate=18 November 2019 |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=30 July 2017}}</ref> as well as runner-up in the [[2018 Chatham Cup#Final|2018 Chatham Cup]].<ref name="background"/>

===Eastern Suburbs===
Just was part of [[Eastern Suburbs AFC|Eastern Suburbs]] winning [[2018–19 New Zealand Football Championship|New Zealand Football Championship]] team, that won the final series of the league, qualifying for the [[2019–20 OFC Champions League|OFC Champions League]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Voerman |first1=Andrew |title=Eastern Suburbs' national league win a showcase for youth development |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/domestic/111691756/eastern-suburbs-national-league-win-a-showcase-for-youth-development |accessdate=18 November 2019 |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=1 April 2019}}</ref> Just finished the season playing in 20 games, scoring 7 goals.<ref>{{cite web |title=Premiership 2018/19 |url=https://us.soccerway.com/national/new-zealand/premiership/20182019/regular-season/r47158/ |website=Soccerway |accessdate=18 November 2019}}</ref>

===FC Helsingør===
In May 2019, FC Helsingør announced that Just would start at the club 1 July.<ref>{{cite web |title=FC Helsingør skriver kontrakt med to unge newzealændere |url=https://www.fchelsingor.dk/2019/05/07/fc-helsingoer-skriver-kontrakt-med-to-unge-newzealaendere/ |website=FC Helsingør |language=da-DK |accessdate=6 August 2022 |archive-date=6 August 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220806071810/https://www.fchelsingor.dk/2019/05/07/fc-helsingoer-skriver-kontrakt-med-to-unge-newzealaendere/ |url-status=dead }}</ref>

===AC Horsens===
On 1 July 2022, FC Helsingør announced that Just had been sold to [[AC Horsens]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Elijah Just skifter til AC Horsens |url=https://www.fchelsingor.dk/2022/08/01/elijah-just-skifter-til-ac-horsens/ |website=FC Helsingør |date=August 2022 |language=da-DK |accessdate=6 August 2022 |archive-date=6 August 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220806071810/https://www.fchelsingor.dk/2022/08/01/elijah-just-skifter-til-ac-horsens/ |url-status=dead }}</ref>

On 21 August 2024, Just signed for Austrian [[2. Liga (Austria)|2. Liga]] club [[SKN St. Pölten]] on a season-long loan with an option to buy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skn-stpoelten.at/skn-news/zwei-neue-sturmer-fur-den-skn|trans-title=Elijah Just and Malcolm Stolt join the pack|title=Elijah Just und Malcolm Stolt verstärken das Rudel|language=German|website=www.skn-stpoelten.at|date=21 August 2024|accessdate=21 August 2024}}</ref>

===Motherwell===
On 9 July 2025, Just signed for [[Scottish Premiership]] club [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]] on a two-year contract for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.motherwellfc.co.uk/2025/07/09/new-zealand-international-elijah-just-lands-in-ml1/ |title=New Zealand international Elijah Just lands in ML1 |publisher=Motherwell F.C. |date=9 July 2025 |access-date=11 July 2025}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cr7pr9j23dyo|title=Motherwell: Elijah Just's rise from Austrian second tier to Premiership standout|date=28 April 2026|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> In his debut season, he was shortlisted for PFA Scotland's Premiership player of the year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/c77m7yd5kypo|title=Claudio Braga, Elijah Just, Tawanda Maswanhise & Lawrence Shankland up for PFA Scotland player of the year award|date=27 April 2026|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

==International career==
===Youth===
Just was born in New Zealand to a German father and Chinese mother.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/ng-interactive/2026/jun/04/world-cup-2026-complete-player-guide|title=World Cup 2026: guide to all 1,248 players|first1=Marcus|last1=Christenson|first2=David|last2=Hills|first3=Steven|last3=Bloor|first4=Garry|last4=Blight|first5=Billy|last5=Munday|date=4 June 2026|via=The Guardian}}</ref> He was part of the [[New Zealand national under-17 football team|New Zealand U-17]] team that won the [[2017 OFC U-17 Championship]], qualifying for the [[2017 FIFA U-17 World Cup|U-17 World Cup]] in India.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dando |first1=Kris |title=Porirua lads help New Zealand to under 17 football World Cup qualification |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/nz-teams/89938385/porirua-lads-help-new-zealand-to-under-17-football-world-cup-qualification |accessdate=18 November 2019 |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=3 March 2017}}</ref> Just played all three games the U-17 team played at the World Cup and was team captain in the second game against [[Paraguay national under-17 football team|Paraguay]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Official Match Report Paraguay v New Zealand |url=https://www.fifa.com/u17worldcup/matches/round=275931/match=300394704/report.html#nosticky |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012065327/http://www.fifa.com/u17worldcup/matches/round=275931/match=300394704/report.html#nosticky |url-status=dead |archive-date=12 October 2017 |website=FIFA |accessdate=18 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=U-17 World Cup India |url=https://us.soccerway.com/international/world/u17-world-cup/2017/group-stage/r43053/ |website=Soccerway |accessdate=18 November 2019}}</ref>

Just was originally called up to be part of the [[New Zealand national under-20 football team|New Zealand U-20]] side to play at the [[2018 OFC U-19 Championship|OFC U-19 Championship]] in [[Tahiti]] but withdraw for club commitments with [[Western Suburbs FC (New Zealand)|Western Suburbs]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hyslop |first1=Liam |title=Young Kiwi footballers Callum McCowatt and Eli Just set for spells at European clubs |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/domestic/106115619/young-kiwi-footballers-callum-mccowatt-and-eli-just-set-for-spells-at-european-clubs |accessdate=18 November 2019 |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=8 August 2018}}</ref> Even though Just didn't play in the OFC U-19 Championship, the team qualified for the [[2019 FIFA U-20 World Cup|U-20 World Cup]] in [[Poland]] and Just was part of the team that travelled to the tournament. He played in 3 games, scoring one goal in their Round of 16 defeat by penalties to [[Colombia national under-20 football team|Colombia U-20]].<ref>{{cite web |title=COLOMBIA U20 VS. NEW ZEALAND U20 1 – 1 |url=https://us.soccerway.com/matches/2019/06/02/world/u20-world-cup/colombia-youth/new-zealand-u20/2988804/ |website=Soccerway |accessdate=18 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Voerman |first1=Andrew |title=Progress made as Fifa Under-20 World Cup campaign ends with heartbreak, not history |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/nz-teams/113201244/progress-made-as-fifa-under20-world-cup-campaign-ends-with-heartbreak-not-history |accessdate=18 November 2019 |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=3 June 2019}}</ref>

===Senior===
On 15 November 2019, Just made his national team debut for [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand]] in a friendly against [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Ireland]], starting in their 1–3 loss.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Voerman |first1=Andrew |title=Callum McCowatt scores on debut as new-look All Whites lose to Republic of Ireland |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/nz-teams/117073735/callum-mccowatt-scores-on-debut-as-newlook-all-whites-lose-to-republic-of-ireland |accessdate=15 November 2019 |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]}}</ref>

On 25 June 2021, Just was called up to the New Zealand squad for the delayed [[Football at the 2020 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament|2020 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/105080?newsfeedId=1275622| title= Squads named for Tokyo 2020| date= 25 June 2021| publisher= [[New Zealand Football]]| language= en| access-date= 25 June 2021| archive-date= 25 June 2021| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20210625021412/https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/105080?newsfeedId=1275622| url-status= dead}}</ref>

Just scored his first international goal against [[Fiji national football team|Fiji]] in their 4–0 win during the [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (OFC)|2022 FIFA World Cup qualifiers]] in Qatar.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rollo |first1=Phillip |title=Chris Wood becomes All Whites' all-time leading scorer with brace against Fiji |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/nz-teams/128124188/chris-wood-becomes-all-whites-alltime-leading-scorer-with-brace-against-fiji |work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=21 March 2022 |language=en}}</ref>

